","1350–Male":"1350–Overleden","1350–Female":"1350–Overleden","1350":"1350","Abt 1439":"circa 1439","Abt 1438":"circa 1438","1425":"1425","1414":"1414","1402":"1402","Aft 1 October 1474":"na 1 oktober 1474","1455":"1455","1398":"1398","1475":"1475","1496":"1496","1474":"1474","1439":"1439","1438":"1438","Bedale, Yorkshire, England":"Bedale, Yorkshire, England","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1398–Aft 1 October 1474":"1398–after 1 October 1474","1398–1474":"1398–1474","1414–1475":"1414–1475","1438–Female":"1438–Deceased","1439–1496":"1439–1496","1350–Male":"1350–Deceased","1350–Female":"1350–Deceased","1350":"1350","Abt 1439":"about 1439","Abt 1438":"about 1438","1425":"1425","1414":"1414","1402":"1402","Aft 1 October 1474":"after 1 October 1474","1455":"1455","1398":"1398","1475":"1475","1496":"1496","1474":"1474","1439":"1439","1438":"1438","Bedale, Yorkshire, England":"Bedale, Yorkshire, England","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Danby","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Danby in North Yorkshire, originally named in Old Norse as <i>Danabȳ</i> ‘settlement of the Danes’, and thus cognate with   Denby  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Denby","meanings":["English (Yorkshire): habitational name from any of the places so named in Yorkshire. A cognate of   Danby  , ‘settlement of the Danes’, but here the Old Norse first element has been replaced by the cognate Old English <i>Dene</i>."]},{"name":"Dansby","meanings":["English: presumably a habitational name from a lost or unidentified place in an area of Scandinavian settlement; perhaps a variant of   Danby  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":57,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Danby II was born in 1398, in Bedale, Yorkshire, England, his father, Thomas Danby, was 49 and his mother, Mary Tanfield, was 48. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Elizabeth Aslaby. His occupation is listed as chief justice of the common pleas, in the time of king edward iv in Bedale, Yorkshire, England. He died after 1 October 1474."},"et":{"1398–Aft 1 October 1474":"1398–pärast 1. oktoobrit 1474","1398–1474":"1398–1474","1414–1475":"1414–1475","1438–Female":"1438–Surnud","1439–1496":"1439–1496","1350–Male":"1350–Surnud","1350–Female":"1350–Surnud","1350":"1350","Abt 1439":"umbes 1439","Abt 1438